            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How this Chinese pension calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                China’s public pension system is complex and fragmented across
                provinces and schemes. This calculator focuses on the
                <strong>basic urban employee pension</strong>
                (城镇职工基本养老保险) and uses a stylised version of the
                official formula to give you an
                <strong>order-of-magnitude estimate</strong> of your future
                monthly benefit.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Basic pension component</h3>
              <p>
                In many cities, the basic pension is linked to the
                <strong>local average wage</strong> and your
                <strong>years of contributions</strong>. A common simplified
                form is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Basic pension</strong> ≈
                  <code
                    >k × Years of contributions × Social average wage at
                    retirement</code
                  >
                </p>
                <p>
                  where <code>k</code> is often around <code>1%</code> (0.01)
                  per year.
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>Our calculator:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Projects the <strong>social average wage</strong> from today
                  to retirement using your growth assumption.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Applies your chosen
                  <strong>basic pension coefficient</strong> (default 0.01) and
                  <strong>years of contributions</strong>.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>2. Individual account pension component</h3>
              <p>
                A portion of contributions is credited to your
                <strong>individual account</strong>. At retirement, the balance
                is converted into a monthly pension using an
                <strong>annuity divisor</strong> set by policy (e.g. 139 months
                at age 60).
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Individual account pension</strong> ≈
                  <code
                    >Individual account balance ÷ Annuity divisor (months)</code
                  >
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>We approximate your individual account balance as:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <code
                    >Balance ≈ Σ [ Wage(t) × Individual account share × (1 +
                    return)^(Years from t to retirement) ]</code
                  >
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                To keep it fast and transparent, we assume your wage grows at a
                constant rate and approximate the sum with a closed-form
                geometric series.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Replacement rate</h3>
              <p>
                The <strong>replacement rate</strong> is a key indicator in
                pension analysis:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Replacement rate</strong> =
                  <code
                    >Total monthly pension ÷ Final monthly wage at
                    retirement</code
                  >
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                International organisations like the OECD and World Bank often
                use replacement rates to compare pension adequacy across
                countries. You can experiment with different contribution years
                and growth assumptions to see how your replacement rate changes.
              </p>

              <h2>Step-by-step: using the Chinese pension calculator</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Enter your current age</strong> and
                  <strong>planned retirement age</strong>. This sets the
                  projection horizon.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Set total contribution years</strong> at retirement.
                  Include past and expected future years.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Input your current wage</strong> and the
                  <strong>current local average wage</strong>. If you don’t know
                  the latter, use the latest figure from your city’s statistics
                  bureau.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Adjust wage growth assumptions</strong> for both your
                  own wage and the social average wage. Higher growth raises
                  both your final wage and the reference wage.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong
                    >Choose contribution and individual account rates.</strong
                  >
                  Defaults reflect typical values but vary by city and over
                  time.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Set the annuity divisor</strong> (e.g. 139 for
                  retirement at 60) and the
                  <strong>basic pension coefficient</strong>
                  (default 0.01).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Click <strong>“Calculate Chinese Pension”</strong> to see your
                  estimated monthly benefits and replacement rate.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>Limitations and caveats</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  The model assumes <strong>constant growth rates</strong> and
                  <strong>stable policy parameters</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  It does <strong>not</strong> distinguish between
                  <strong>urban employee</strong> and
                  <strong>urban/rural resident</strong>
                  schemes, nor does it cover special regimes for civil servants
                  or SOE workers.
                </li>
                <li>
                  It ignores <strong>indexation rules</strong> after retirement
                  (how pensions are adjusted for inflation and wage growth).
                </li>
                <li>
                  It does not include <strong>enterprise annuities</strong>,
                  <strong>occupational pensions</strong>, or
                  <strong>commercial pension products</strong>.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Because China’s pension system is undergoing reform and remains
                highly decentralised, your actual benefit may differ
                significantly from this estimate.
              </p>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>
                Is this calculator suitable for migrant workers or flexible
                employment?
              </h3>
              <p>
                Many migrant workers and flexible employees participate in the
                urban employee pension but with
                <strong>interrupted contributions</strong> or contributions in
                multiple cities. This calculator can still be used as a rough
                guide, but you should:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Use your
                  <strong>best estimate of total contribution years</strong>
                  across all locations.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Use a <strong>conservative wage</strong> and growth assumption
                  if your income is volatile.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>What if I contribute more than the minimum 15 years?</h3>
              <p>
                In the simplified formula,
                <strong>each additional year</strong> of contributions increases
                your basic pension by roughly
                <code>k × Social average wage</code>. It also increases your
                individual account balance. You can adjust the
                <strong>years of contributions</strong> field to see the impact.
              </p>

              <h3>How do demographic changes in China affect my pension?</h3>
              <p>
                Research from institutions like the <strong>OECD</strong>,
                <strong>Brookings</strong>, and various Chinese think tanks
                highlights that population ageing and a shrinking workforce put
                <strong>financial pressure</strong> on the system. Policy
                responses may include:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Gradually <strong>raising retirement ages</strong>.</li>
                <li>
                  Adjusting <strong>contribution rates</strong> or
                  <strong>benefit formulas</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Expanding <strong>private and occupational pensions</strong>.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                This calculator cannot predict future reforms; it simply shows
                how today’s stylised rules work.
              </p>

              <h3>
                Where can I get official information about my Chinese pension?
              </h3>
              <p>For authoritative information, consult:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Your local
                  <strong>Human Resources and Social Security Bureau</strong>
                  (人力资源和社会保障局).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Official statements from the
                  <strong
                    >Ministry of Human Resources and Social Security
                    (MOHRSS)</strong
                  >.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Annual statements from your employer’s HR or payroll
                  department.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Use this calculator as a learning tool, not as a substitute for
                official records or professional advice.
              </p>
